[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] In software engineering, **CI/CD** or **CICD** is the combined practices of continuous integration (CI) and continuous delivery (CD) or, less often, continuous deployment.
[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] They are sometimes referred to collectively as continuous development or continuous software development.
[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] Producing software in short cycles with high speed and frequency so that reliable software can be released at any time, with a simple and repeatable deployment process when deciding to deploy.
[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] Automatic rollout of new software functionality.
[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] When these three processes occur in order, they may be described as a "CI/CD pipeline".
[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] CI/CD bridges the gaps between development and operation activities and teams by enforcing automation in building, testing and deployment of applications.
[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] CI/CD services compile the incremental code changes made by developers, then link and package them into software deliverables.
[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] Automated tests verify the software functionality, and automated deployment services deliver them to end users.
[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] The aim is to increase early defect discovery, increase productivity, and provide faster release cycles.
[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] The process contrasts with traditional methods where a collection of software updates were integrated into one large batch before deploying the newer version.
[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] of software applications throughout its development life cycle.
[src:sast-dast-integration/ci-cd] The CI/CD practice, or *CI/CD pipeline*, forms the backbone of modern day DevOps operations.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:sast-dast-integration/devsecops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] On the other side, a DAST tool is a program which communicates with a web application through the web front-end in order to identify potential security vulnerabilities in the web application and architectural weaknesses.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] Unlike static application security testing tools, DAST tools do not have access to the source code and therefore detect vulnerabilities by actually performing attacks.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] DAST tools allow sophisticated scans, detecting vulnerabilities with minimal user interactions once configured with host name, crawling parameters and authentication credentials.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] These tools will attempt to detect vulnerabilities in query strings, headers, fragments, verbs (GET/POST/PUT) and DOM injection.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] DAST tools facilitate the automated review of a web application with the express purpose of discovering security vulnerabilities and are required to comply with various regulatory requirements.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] Web application scanners can look for a wide variety of vulnerabilities, such as input/output validation: (e.g. cross-site scripting and SQL injection), specific application problems and server configuration mistakes.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] Commercial scanners are a category of web-assessment tools which need to be purchased.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] Some scanners include some free features but most need to be bought for full access to the tool's power.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] Open-source scanners are often free of cost to the user.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] These tools can detect vulnerabilities of the finalized release candidate versions prior to shipping.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] Scanners simulate a malicious user by attacking and probing, identifying results which are not part of the expected result set, allowing for a realistic attack simulation.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] The big advantage of these types of tools are that they can scan year-round to be constantly searching for vulnerabilities.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] With new vulnerabilities being discovered regularly this allows companies to find and patch vulnerabilities before they can become exploited.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] As a dynamic testing tool, web scanners are not language-dependent.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] A web application scanner is able to scan engine-driven web applications.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] Attackers use the same tools, so if the tools can find a vulnerability, so can attackers.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] While scanning with a DAST tool, data may be overwritten or malicious payloads injected into the subject site.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] Sites should be scanned in a production-like but non-production environment to ensure accurate results while protecting the data in the production environment.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] Because the tool is implementing a dynamic testing method, it cannot cover 100% of the source code of the application and then, the application itself.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] The penetration tester should look at the coverage of the web application or of its attack surface to know if the tool was configured correctly or was able to understand the web application.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] The tool cannot implement all variants of attacks for a given vulnerability.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] So the tools generally have a predefined list of attacks and do not generate the attack payloads depending on the tested web application.
[src:sast-dast-integration/dynamic-application-security-testing] Some tools are also quite limited in their understanding of the behavior of applications with dynamic content such as JavaScript and Flash.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Unlike dynamic application security testing (DAST) tools for black-box testing of application functionality, SAST tools focus on the code content of the application, white-box testing.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] A SAST tool scans the source code of applications and their components to identify potential security vulnerabilities in their software and architecture.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Static analysis tools can detect an estimated 50% of existing security vulnerabilities in tested applications.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] In the software development life cycle (SDLC), SAST is performed early in the development process and at code level, and also when all pieces of code and components are put together in a consistent testing environment.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] SAST is also used for software quality assurance, even if the many resulting false positives impede its adoption by developers.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] SAST tools are integrated into the development process to help development teams as they are primarily focusing on developing and delivering software respecting requested specifications.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] SAST tools, like other security tools, focus on reducing the risk of downtime of applications or that private information stored in applications is not compromised.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Application security tests conducted before their release include static application security testing (SAST), dynamic application security testing (DAST), and interactive application security testing (IAST), which is a combination of the two.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Static analysis tools examine the text of a program syntactically.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] They look for a fixed set of patterns or rules in the source code.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Theoretically, they can also examine a compiled form of the software.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] This technique relies on instrumentation of the code to do the mapping between compiled components and source code components to identify issues.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Static analysis can be done manually as a code review or auditing of the code for different purposes, including security, but it is time-consuming.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] The precision of SAST tools is determined by their scope of analysis and the specific techniques used to identify vulnerabilities.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] The scope of the analysis determines its accuracy and capacity to detect vulnerabilities using contextual information.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] SAST tools, unlike DAST tools, give developers real-time feedback, and help them secure flaws before they move the code to the next level.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] At a function level, a common technique is the construction of an Abstract syntax tree to control the flow of data within the function.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Since the late 90s, the need to adapt to business challenges has transformed software development with componentization enforced by processes and organization of development teams.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Following the flow of data between all the components of an application or group of applications allows validation of required calls to dedicated procedures for sanitization and that proper actions are taken to taint data in specific pieces of code.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] The rise of web applications entailed testing them: Verizon Data Breach reported in 2016 that 40% of all data breaches use web application vulnerabilities.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Both external security validations and a focus on internal threats have risen.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] The Clearswift Insider Threat Index (CITI) has reported that 92% of their respondents in a 2015 survey said they had experienced IT or security incidents in the previous 12 months and that 74% of these breaches were originated by insiders.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Lee Hadlington categorized internal threats in 3 categories: malicious, accidental, and unintentional.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Mobile applications' explosive growth implies securing applications earlier in the development process to reduce malicious code development.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] The earlier a vulnerability is fixed in the SDLC, the cheaper it is to fix.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Costs to fix in development are 10 times lower than in testing, and 100 times lower than in production.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] SAST tools run automatically, either at the code level or application-level and do not require interaction.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] When integrated into a CI/CD context, SAST tools can be used to automatically stop the integration process if critical vulnerabilities are identified.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Another advantage over other types of testing is that SAST tools scan the entire source code, while dynamic application security testing tools cover its execution, possibly missing part of the application or unsecured configuration in configuration files.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] SAST tools can offer extended functionalities such as quality and architectural testing.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] There is a direct correlation between software quality and security.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Bad quality software is also poorly secured software.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Even though developers are positive about the usage of SAST tools, there are different challenges to their adoption.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] As an example, research shows that despite the long output generated by these tools, they may lack usability.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] With Agile Processes in software development, early integration of SAST generates many bugs, as developers using this framework focus first on features and delivery.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] Scanning many lines of code with SAST tools may result in hundreds or thousands of vulnerability warnings for a single application.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] It can generate many false positives, increasing investigation time and reducing trust in such tools.
[src:sast-dast-integration/static-application-security-testing] This is particularly the case when the context of the vulnerability cannot be caught by the tool.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet is intended to provide guidance on the vulnerability disclosure process for both security researchers and organizations.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] This is an area where collaboration is extremely important, but that can often result in conflict between the two parties.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] There are a number of different models that can be followed when disclosing vulnerabilities, which are listed in the sections below.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] In the private disclosure model, the vulnerability is reported privately to the organization.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] The organization may choose to publish the details of the vulnerabilities, but this is done at the discretion of the organization, not the researcher, meaning that many vulnerabilities may never be made public.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] The majority of bug bounty programs require that the researcher follows this model.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] The main problem with this model is that if the vendor is unresponsive, or decides not to fix the vulnerability, then the details may never be made public.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Historically this has lead to researchers getting fed up with companies ignoring and trying to hide vulnerabilities, leading them to the full disclosure approach.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] With the full disclosure approach, the full details of the vulnerability are made public as soon as they are identified.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] This means that the full details (sometimes including exploit code) are available to attackers, often before a patch is available.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] The full disclosure approach is primarily used in response or organizations ignoring reported vulnerabilities, in order to put pressure on them to develop and publish a fix.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] This makes the full disclosure approach very controversial, and it is seen as irresponsible by many people.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Generally it should only be considered as a last resort, when all other methods have failed, or when exploit code is already publicly available.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Responsible disclosure attempts to find a reasonable middle ground between these two approaches.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] With responsible disclosure, the initial report is made privately, but with the full details being published once a patch has been made available (sometimes with a delay to allow more time for the patches to be installed).
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] In many cases, the researcher also provides a deadline for the organization to respond to the report, or to provide a patch.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] If this deadline is not met, then the researcher may adopt the full disclosure approach, and publish the full details.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Google's Project Zero adopts a similar approach, where the full details of the vulnerability are published after 90 days regardless of whether or not the organization has published a patch.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] This section is intended to provide guidance for security researchers on how to report vulnerabilities to organizations.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Before carrying out any security research or reporting vulnerabilities, **ensure that you know and understand the laws in your jurisdiction**.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet **does not constitute legal advice, and should not be taken as such.**.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] The first step in reporting a vulnerability is finding the appropriate person to report it to.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Although some organizations have clearly published disclosure policies, many do not, so it can be difficult to find the correct place to report the issue.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] When reaching out to people who are not dedicated security contacts, request the details for a relevant member of staff, rather than disclosing the vulnerability details to whoever accepts the initial contact (especially over social media).
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] If it is not possible to contact the organization directly, a national or sector-based CERT may be able to assist.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Once a security contact has been identified, an initial report should be made of the details of the vulnerability.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Ideally this should be done over an encrypted channel (such as the use of PGP keys), although many organizations do not support this.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] In many cases, especially in smaller organizations, the security reports may be handled by developers or IT staff who do not have a security background.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] This means that they may not be familiar with many security concepts or terminology, so reports should be written in clear and simple terms.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] It may also be beneficial to provide a recommendation on how the issue could be mitigated or resolved.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] However, unless the details of the system or application are known, or you are very confident in the recommendation then it may be better to point the developers to some more general guidance (such as an OWASP cheat sheet).
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] If you are planning to publish the details of the vulnerability after a period of time (as per some responsible disclosure policies), then this should be clearly communicated in the initial email - but try to do so in a tone that doesn't sound threatening to the recipient.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] If the organization does not have an established bug bounty program, then avoid asking about payments or rewards in the initial contact - leave it until the issue has been acknowledged (or ideally fixed).
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] In particular, **do not demand payment before revealing the details of the vulnerability**.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] At best this will look like an attempt to scam the company, at worst it may constitute extortion.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] While simpler vulnerabilities might be resolved solely from the initial report, in many cases there will be a number of emails back and forth between the researcher and the organization.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Especially for more complex vulnerabilities, the developers or administrators may ask for additional information or recommendations on how to resolve the issue.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] They may also ask for assistance in retesting the issue once a fix has been implemented.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Although there is no obligation to carry out this retesting, as long as the request is reasonable then and providing feedback on the fixes is very beneficial.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] It may also be necessary to chase up the organization if they become unresponsive, or if the established deadline for publicly disclosing the vulnerability is approaching.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Ensure that this communication stays professional and positive - if the disclosure process becomes hostile then neither party will benefit.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Be patient if it's taking a while for the issue to be resolved.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] The developers may be under significant pressure from different people within the organization, and may not be able to be fully open in their communication.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Triaging, developing, reviewing, testing and deploying a fix within in an enterprise environment takes **significantly** more time than most researchers expect, and being constantly hassled for updates just adds another level of pressure on the developers.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Despite every effort that you make, some organizations are not interested in security, are impossible to contact, or may be actively hostile to researchers disclosing vulnerabilities.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] In some cases they may even threaten to take legal action against researchers.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] When this happens it is very disheartening for the researcher - it is important not to take this personally.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] When this happens, there are a number of options that can be taken.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] There are many organizations who have a genuine interest in security, and are very open and co-operative with security researchers.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Unless the vulnerability is extremely serious, **it is not worth burning yourself out, or risking your career and livelihood over an organization who doesn't care**.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Once a vulnerability has been patched (or not), then a decision needs to be made about publishing the details.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] This should ideally be done through discussion with the vendor, and at a minimum the vendor should be notified that you intend to publish, and provided with a link to the published details.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Some organizations may request that you do not publish the details at all, or that you delay publication to allow more time to their users to install security patches.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] In the interest of maintaining a positive relationship with the organization, it is worth trying to find a compromise position on this.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Whether to publish working proof of concept (or functional exploit code) is a subject of debate.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Some people will view this as an unethical move, and will argue that by doing so you are directly helping criminals compromise their users.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] On the other hand, the code can be used to both system administrators and penetration testers to test their systems, and attackers will be able to develop or reverse engineering working exploit code if the vulnerability is sufficiently valuable.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] If you are publishing the details in hostile circumstances (such as an unresponsive organization, or after a stated period of time has elapsed) then you may face threats and even legal action.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Whether there is any legal basis for this will depend on your jurisdiction, and whether you signed any form of non-disclosure agreement with the organization.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Make sure you understand your legal position before doing so.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Note that many bug bounty programs forbid researchers from publishing the details without the agreement of the organization.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] If you choose to do so, you may forfeit the bounty or be banned from the platform - so read the rules of the program before publishing.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] This section is intended to provide guidance for organizations on how to accept and receive vulnerability reports.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Bug bounty programs incentivize researchers to identify and report vulnerabilities to organizations by offering rewards.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] These are usually monetary, but can also be physical items (swag).
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] The process is often managed through a third party such as BugCrowd or HackerOne, who provide mediation between researchers and organizations.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Bug bounty have been adopted by many large organizations such as Microsoft, and are starting to be used outside of the commercial sector, including the US Department of Defense.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] However, for smaller organizations they can bring significant challenges, and require a substantial investment of time and resources.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Despite these potential issues, bug bounty programs are a great way to identify vulnerabilities in applications and systems.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] However, they should only be used by organizations that already have a mature vulnerability disclosure process, supported by strong internal processes to resolve vulnerabilities.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] The most important step in the process is providing a way for security researchers to contact your organization.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] The easier it is for them to do so, the more likely it is that you'll receive security reports.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] It is also important to ensure that frontline staff (such as those who monitor the main contact address, web chat and phone lines) are aware of how to handle reports of security issues, and who to escalate these reports to within the organization.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Alongside the contact details, it is also good to provide some guidelines for researchers to follow when reporting vulnerabilities.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Communication between researchers and organizations is often one of the hardest points of the vulnerability disclosure process, and can easily leave both sides frustrated and unhappy with the process.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Throughout the process, provide regular updates of the current status, and the expected timeline to triage and fix the vulnerability.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Even if there is no firm timeline for these, the ongoing communication provides some reassurance that the vulnerability hasn't been forgotten about.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Some individuals may approach an organization claiming to have found a vulnerability, and demanding payment before sharing the details.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Although these requests *may* be legitimate, in many cases they are simply scams.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] One option is to request that they carry out the disclosure through a mediated bug bounty platform, which can provide a level of protection for both sides, as scammers are unlikely to be willing to use these platforms.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Once the vulnerability has been resolved (and retested), the details should be published in a security advisory for the software.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] It is important to remember that publishing the details of security issues **does not make the vendor look bad**.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] All software has security vulnerabilities, and demonstrating a clear and established process for handling and disclosing them gives far more confidence in the security of the software than trying to hide the issues.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Security advisories should be easy for developers and system administrators to find.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Some researchers may publish their own technical write ups of the vulnerability, which will usually include the full details required to exploit it (and sometimes even working exploit code).
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] For more serious vulnerabilities, it may be sensible to ask the researcher to delay publishing the full details for a period of time (such as a week), in order to give system administrators more time to install the patches before exploit code is available.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] However, once the patch has been releases, attackers will be able to reverse engineer the vulnerability and develop their own exploit code, so there is limited value to delaying the full release.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] For vulnerabilities in private systems, a decision needs to be made about whether the details should be published once the vulnerability has been resolved.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Most bug bounty programs give organizations the option about whether to disclose the details once the issue has been resolved, although it is not typically required.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Publishing these details helps to demonstrate that the organization is taking proactive and transparent approach to security, but can also result in potentially embarrassing omissions and misconfigurations being made public.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] In the event of a future compromise or data breach, they could also potentially be used as evidence of a weak security culture within the organization.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] Additionally, they may expose technical details about internal, and could help attackers identify other similar issues.
[src:sast-dast-integration/vulnerability-disclosure-cheat-sheet] As such, this decision should be carefully evaluated, and it may be wise to take legal advice.
